node.text: First launched in 1936, the 6631-T Luxus table lamp quickly became the archetype of the KAISER idell™ lighting series, exemplifying designer Christian Dell’s graceful, uncluttered style.

The Series 7™ chair is an icon in modern furniture history, designed by Arne Jacobsen in 1955. By raising the height of the Junior Series 7 chair and adding a footrest, the chair allows children to sit comfortably at the table.

Versatile and minimalist, Fritz Hansen's Kaiser idell™ 6556-T lamp is renowned for its iconic shape and timeless appeal. Now reimagined in a matte grey hue, it brings together past and present in a union of timeless Bauhaus design and modern Nordic sensibilities. 

Learn more via the link in bio.

With its soft, organic lines, Arne Jacobsen's Swan™ chair has a strong architectural appeal that has secured its status as an icon of Danish design.

Learn more about the pioneering piece via the link in bio.

Colour is powerful. My Sense of Colour brings to life the impact that colour has on our emotions, thoughts and feelings when combined with extraordinary design. Tap the link in bio to discover Fritz Hansen's colourful universe, seen through the eyes of creatives.

Shaped like a cross in plexiglass, the Cross-Plex™ is a simple yet refined table lamp with a natural ability to lift the ambience of any space. 

Click the link in bio to discover more.

Fred™ takes its design cues from the broad wings, distinctive bill and gently curved body of the pelican – and its name from the Danish word for peace. Sculpted in ash or oak, the lounge chair has a lightness that belies its strength.

Discover more via the link in bio.

Fritz Hansen's new and improved Oxford™ chair, designed by Arne Jacobsen, is optimised in comfort for a new generation of workspaces. Shaped to support the body as it sits, it's offered in a low or medium back version with or without armrests that tuck neatly under tables. Upholstered in leather or fabric to enhance its timeless aesthetic, the flexible design is equally suited to a home as it is an office.

Tap the link in bio to create yours.

A mobile side table design with a sophisticated, architectural edge. Arne Jacobsen originally designed this elegant trolley for his tea. It has now been revived from the Fritz Hansen archive to serve as a bar cart, serving trolley or side table.

The new Oxford™ chair showcases minimalist design and modern ergonomics, making Arne Jacobsen’s classic piece more comfortable than ever before. Ideal at home or in the office, the timeless design offers supreme sitting comfort and customisation. 

Discover more via the link in bio.

The Lissoni™ sofa is customisable to your needs. Choose from 2- or 3-seater versions, four base finish options, and premium leather or upholstery fabric from our comprehensive range. Tap the link in bio to configure your own.
Fritz Hansen reimagines Arne Jacobsen's original Drop™ chair design in contemporary colours. Clay, beige, green and rose and powder-coated base finishes ensure its relevance today and tomorrow.

Danish architect and cabinetmaker Poul Kjærholm made his name creating unique and timeless furniture of outstanding beauty and exceptional quality. The straight lines and subtle curves of his now-iconic furniture reflect his search for ideal forms. The pure, abstract shapes of his PK80™ daybed, PK91™ folding stool, PK25™ chair and PK33™ stool focus attention on materials.

Discover more on his designs via the link in bio.

Elegant, muted hues add a sense of modern sophistication to the embracing Drop chair, designed by Arne Jacobsen in 1958 for Copenhagen’s SAS Royal Hotel. The seven new and sophisticated shades and powder-coated base finishes maintain the legacy of this timeless design.

Discover more about the iconic design by tapping the link in bio.

Copyright: Jørgen Strüwing.

Fritz Hansen presents My Sense of Colour with the renowned Japanese architect Kengo Kuma. Shown on Arne Jacobsen’s iconic Series 7™ chair, Deep Clay is a soft neutral, perfect for modern interiors. See more via link in bio.

Seven sophisticated colours and new, powder-coated base finishes maintain the legacy of Arne Jacobsen’s timeless Drop™ chair by Fritz Hansen. Harmonious shades of clay, beige, green and rose honour the original design yet ensure its relevance to a modern audience. Perfectly matching the Arne Jacobsen stacking chair series in colours curated by Carla Sozzani, the new palette offers a cohesive look for mixing and matching across designs.

Click the link in bio to discover the new colours.
Stay home Sunday. Sheepskin ups the snuggle factor on the Let™ lounge chair – designed for Fritz Hansen by Sebastian Herkner – creating a cosy, intimate spot filled with soft texture.

The new Clam™ pendant light, designed for Fritz Hansen by Ahm and Lund, opens to reveal a pearlescent source of light within its mouth-blown opal glass shades. The perfectly balanced design elevates any room with its considered combination of form and ambiance.

Discover more by visiting the link in bio.

Characterised by its three-legged, satin-brushed stainless steel frame, the PK11™ strikes the perfect balance between soft curves and bold angles. Designed by Poul Kjærholm in 1957, it is a complex yet elegant chair, created as a companion to the PK51™ worktable.

Fritz Hansen’s stacking chairs by Arne Jacobsen are swathed in a palette of hues to evoke the senses. My Sense of Colour adds emotions and feelings to the iconic designs, seen through the eyes of creative personalities. Discover what colour means to them via the link in bio.
